# Common Testing Rule

This team treats verification as mandatory, but test depth should match task scope.

## Verification baseline

Every meaningful code change must be verified by `runner`.
Verification may include one or more of:
- unit tests
- integration tests
- end-to-end checks
- static analysis
- type checks
- build validation
- targeted reproduction scripts

## Test depth policy

### Always expected
- at least one relevant verification step for every code change
- reproduction of the bug before fixing it, when practical
- focused checks first, broader checks second

### Usually expected
- unit tests for new logic or bug fixes
- integration tests when boundaries between modules, I/O, databases, subprocesses, or services are involved

### Conditionally expected
- end-to-end tests only for critical user flows, pipelines, or interface-level guarantees
- coverage measurement when the repository already supports it or when the task explicitly asks for it

## TDD policy

Prefer test-first work for new behavior and bug fixes.
Use a practical version of RED → GREEN → REFACTOR when it improves reliability.
Do not block small operational fixes on ceremonial test-first steps if a faster, well-verified path is more appropriate.

## Failure handling

If tests fail, `runner` must identify whether the likely cause is:
- implementation defect
- stale or incorrect test
- broken environment or harness
- incomplete plan or wrong scope

Then `leader` decides whether work returns to `coder` or `planner`.

## Reporting requirements

`runner` should report:
- commands executed
- scope of verification
- PASS / FAIL / BLOCKED
- failing tests or errors
- what remains unverified
